1
00:00:01,835 --> 00:00:05,234
Welcome to the Brave commentary.
I'm your host Mark Andrews.

2
00:00:05,806 --> 00:00:07,946
I'm the director of Brave.
And I'm here with...

3
00:00:08,342 --> 00:00:10,212
Steve Purcell,
co-director and co-writer.

4
00:00:10,577 --> 00:00:11,747
Nick Smith, editor.

5
00:00:12,012 --> 00:00:14,202
I'm Brian Larsen, story supervisor.

6
00:00:14,615 --> 00:00:16,135
We were thinking
that with the Disney castle

7
00:00:16,450 --> 00:00:19,520
we would actually change it into
the Dun Broch Castle.

8
00:00:20,053 --> 00:00:20,983
There was a discussion

9
00:00:21,221 --> 00:00:23,881
but we decided just to go with
the original Disney castle.

10
00:00:24,358 --> 00:00:25,258
We talk about a lot of things.

11
00:00:25,492 --> 00:00:27,332
We talked about a lot of things
over the course of the film.

12
00:00:27,694 --> 00:00:29,244
Wasn't there something you
wanted to do on the Pixar logo?

13
00:00:29,563 --> 00:00:31,403
-Yeah, we wanted...
-The bagpipe thing.

14
00:00:31,765 --> 00:00:33,785
We wanted him to come in
with some bagpipes.

15
00:00:34,167 --> 00:00:35,537
-Or at least give him a kilt.
-And a kilt?

16
00:00:35,836 --> 00:00:38,936
No when he jumped in it would be...
A bagpipe.

17
00:00:39,473 --> 00:00:41,963
-Then a groan...
-Then a... Yeah.

18
00:00:46,079 --> 00:00:47,159
-We should do that.
-It's not too late.

19
00:00:47,414 --> 00:00:49,314
-We just did.
-Yeah.

20
00:00:49,683 --> 00:00:54,663
So, the beginning of Brave
started very differently for a little while.

21
00:00:55,455 --> 00:00:57,223
l had this whole scene where

22
00:00:57,324 --> 00:01:01,574
Fergus was hunting
through the snow to find Mor'du

23
00:01:02,262 --> 00:01:05,832
and we were going to
give the audience this experience of

24
00:01:06,433 --> 00:01:08,603
encountering Mor'du
so that we'd know who he was

25
00:01:09,002 --> 00:01:11,551
and know why Fergus
was missing the leg

26
00:01:12,005 --> 00:01:14,464
and establish his hatred for bears.

27
00:01:14,908 --> 00:01:20,148
Almost this Captain Ahab to Moby Dick,
kind of lust to destroy this bear

28
00:01:20,981 --> 00:01:22,500
which plays into the story later.

29
00:01:22,816 --> 00:01:26,276
We boarded it. We put it through layout.
We animated it.

30
00:01:26,853 --> 00:01:29,603
We started to render it
and then in one screening

31
00:01:30,090 --> 00:01:33,570
we realized that we're too far away
from our main character, Merida.

32
00:01:34,161 --> 00:01:38,441
So there was this idea about
showing Merida when she was younger.

33
00:01:39,132 --> 00:01:43,492
Of showing Merida and her mother
Elinor when everything was good.

34
00:01:44,204 --> 00:01:48,863
So that after the sequence opened
and we flash forward in time,

35
00:01:49,610 --> 00:01:51,980
we pick them up
and now their relationship is strained.

36
00:01:52,412 --> 00:01:54,552
Well, that's what ultimately this scene,
I think, is trying to really set up

37
00:01:54,948 --> 00:01:59,398
is, like, their relationship, family,
Mor'du, the wisps, the bow.

38
00:02:00,120 --> 00:02:02,140
There was so much that this scene
was trying to incorporate

39
00:02:02,556 --> 00:02:03,456
-and like you were saying with...
-Right.

40
00:02:03,690 --> 00:02:05,000
-And Dad's relationship with Mom, too.
-Yeah.

41
00:02:05,292 --> 00:02:06,842
And get it through organically.

42
00:02:07,160 --> 00:02:09,880
We see her and her mom having
this great relationship where

43
00:02:10,364 --> 00:02:12,094
they're playing and loving each other.

44
00:02:12,432 --> 00:02:17,061
Dad gives her a bow for the birthday,
so this creates her love for the bow.

45
00:02:17,804 --> 00:02:21,344
And we establish the wisps here
that lead you to your fate.

46
00:02:21,942 --> 00:02:23,642
And in this case lead her away

47
00:02:23,977 --> 00:02:26,877
from getting eaten by
this big, evil, demon bear.

48
00:02:27,381 --> 00:02:31,481
But then this is that encounter
where we call Mor'du by name

49
00:02:32,152 --> 00:02:34,841
and still get the encounter
between Fergus.

50
00:02:35,322 --> 00:02:36,722
Well, originally we had Merida alone.

51
00:02:37,024 --> 00:02:38,394
Right, sneaking out of the castle.

52
00:02:38,692 --> 00:02:40,392
Yeah, we've had
many different openings.

53
00:02:40,727 --> 00:02:42,567
And actually
it's surprising to think back on

54
00:02:42,929 --> 00:02:45,149
how often we would do scenes that had

55
00:02:45,565 --> 00:02:47,025
only a couple of
the characters together.

56
00:02:47,334 --> 00:02:48,914
And I think there's a lot to be said for

57
00:02:49,236 --> 00:02:51,486
putting all the characters together
right away,

58
00:02:51,905 --> 00:02:53,955
so you can kind of
feel their dynamic from the get-go.

59
00:02:54,341 --> 00:02:57,411
So we had to very quickly
create a brand new character.

60
00:02:57,944 --> 00:02:59,083
That young Merida here.

61
00:02:59,346 --> 00:03:02,366
And to get her right, we were
talking about taking a triplet

62
00:03:02,883 --> 00:03:04,613
-and putting longer hair on it.
-Yeah.

63
00:03:04,951 --> 00:03:08,581
We actually took Merida
and scaled her down to a little girl.

64
00:03:09,189 --> 00:03:10,939
Pulled in the body
and got the proportions right.

65
00:03:11,291 --> 00:03:13,041
Then we really had to
subtly adjust the face.

66
00:03:13,393 --> 00:03:15,763
And we had to have
a whole new hair rig,

67
00:03:16,196 --> 00:03:17,216
our new hairdo done.

68
00:03:17,464 --> 00:03:19,424
And everybody just rallied
and did a marvelous job.

69
00:03:19,800 --> 00:03:21,610
And we have this
super-cute little girl now.

70
00:03:21,968 --> 00:03:23,518
And we also had to find a voice, too.

71
00:03:23,837 --> 00:03:26,857
And Patrick Doyle, our composer,
found this girl to sing the lullaby.

72
00:03:27,374 --> 00:03:28,924
The lullaby, yeah.

73
00:03:29,276 --> 00:03:31,616
And thought that she might work.
And you went over and...

74
00:03:32,045 --> 00:03:34,035
Met her and then we got the song.

75
00:03:34,414 --> 00:03:36,874
And then I said, "Hey, I have this scene
l want you to try."

76
00:03:37,317 --> 00:03:38,807
-What was her name?
-It was Peigi.

77
00:03:39,119 --> 00:03:41,779
And she said, "Sure,"
and she'd never kind of acted before.

78
00:03:42,255 --> 00:03:44,565
But then she did the voice
and knocked it out of the park.

79
00:03:44,991 --> 00:03:46,721
We auditioned a bunch of little girls.

80
00:03:47,060 --> 00:03:49,460
But it turns out
Peigi was the most natural.

81
00:03:49,896 --> 00:03:52,916
And two sessions and she nailed it.

82
00:03:53,433 --> 00:03:56,043
-She had a sweet voice.
-It was unpolished in a really sweet way.

83
00:03:57,504 --> 00:04:00,603
And then we get into the attack here.
So everything is fate.

84
00:04:01,141 --> 00:04:04,241
You can almost say that
the wisps led this encounter to happen

85
00:04:04,778 --> 00:04:08,208
to be resolved
several years down the road.

86
00:04:08,782 --> 00:04:11,392
This is the inciting incident
to kind of bring them all off.

87
00:04:11,852 --> 00:04:15,421
And then to really get this big hit,
l really wanted this.

88
00:04:15,522 --> 00:04:16,832
-Well, it's two great bookends.
-Yeah.

89
00:04:17,124 --> 00:04:20,194
The beginning and the end of the family
coming together to fight Mor'du.

90
00:04:20,761 --> 00:04:22,491
And so this is the opening here,

91
00:04:23,330 --> 00:04:25,931
once we go through
the coming out of the clouds

92
00:04:26,032 --> 00:04:27,232
and going into
the Highlands of Scotland

93
00:04:27,501 --> 00:04:28,760
and coming down to find the castle.

94
00:04:29,035 --> 00:04:31,995
It was my homage to
The Sound Of Music.

95
00:04:32,506 --> 00:04:34,585
And I thought that
getting into the movies...

96
00:04:34,975 --> 00:04:36,265
‘Cause that used to be our opening,

97
00:04:36,543 --> 00:04:40,323
as just starting coming out of cloud
into images of Scotland.

98
00:04:40,947 --> 00:04:44,227
But I really wanted to
transport the audience.

99
00:04:44,785 --> 00:04:46,685
And there's several movies
that really do this well.

100
00:04:47,053 --> 00:04:50,013
I think Braveheart does it well
by coming across the water

101
00:04:50,524 --> 00:04:52,634
and rising up over
the Scottish Highlands.

102
00:04:53,026 --> 00:04:55,366
Which I also do in this sequence.

103
00:04:55,796 --> 00:04:57,756
And then, in Sound Of Music

104
00:04:58,131 --> 00:05:01,820
to just give us a sense of this world
that we're going to be in,

105
00:05:02,435 --> 00:05:03,985
I thought was very important.

106
00:05:05,105 --> 00:05:06,745
This next scene right here,

107
00:05:07,073 --> 00:05:09,293
actually Mark choreographed this
and we filmed it.

108
00:05:09,709 --> 00:05:12,579
This fight scene right here,
Mark was actually Fergus.

109
00:05:13,079 --> 00:05:14,509
You should be able to
find that on the Blu-ray.

110
00:05:14,848 --> 00:05:15,988
-And were you...
-l was in there.

111
00:05:16,249 --> 00:05:17,329
Yeah, I was one of the guys
who gets kicked.

112
00:05:17,584 --> 00:05:19,514
How many guys? Did you actually
do it with that many guys?

113
00:05:19,886 --> 00:05:21,086
I did it with that many guys, yeah.

114
00:05:21,354 --> 00:05:23,464
We choreographed the whole thing.

115
00:05:23,857 --> 00:05:27,427
The animators were really into
all the archery and the sword fighting.

116
00:05:28,028 --> 00:05:30,278
And I was teaching them the swords

117
00:05:30,697 --> 00:05:32,337
and doing all the choreography
and we were filming it.

118
00:05:32,666 --> 00:05:34,945
-So they can really go in there...
-'Cause you're trained in this, right?

119
00:05:35,368 --> 00:05:37,978
lam. But so they could go in there,
‘cause it's those details of

120
00:05:38,438 --> 00:05:40,658
how you move and where you
shift your weight and all that stuff.

121
00:05:41,074 --> 00:05:43,684
And they really wanted to nail it
and get it down.

122
00:05:45,745 --> 00:05:47,555
There we see Merida as a teenager.

123
00:05:47,914 --> 00:05:49,724
But I wanted to,
as soon as the doors opened,

124
00:05:50,083 --> 00:05:51,453
find her doing something wrong.

125
00:05:51,751 --> 00:05:53,330
She's just doing the stuff
that she wants to do,

126
00:05:53,653 --> 00:05:56,463
like eating that apple,
but she's constantly getting in trouble

127
00:05:56,957 --> 00:05:59,147
or being frowned upon by her mother.

128
00:05:59,559 --> 00:06:01,579
Just so that we get that instant

129
00:06:01,962 --> 00:06:05,182
change of dynamics of their relationship
from the beginning of the film.

130
00:06:05,732 --> 00:06:08,312
We want a chance to see Mom
and Merida together.

131
00:06:08,768 --> 00:06:10,347
So we could see,
even in their body language,

132
00:06:10,670 --> 00:06:11,980
how different they are as characters.

133
00:06:12,272 --> 00:06:15,402
Where Mom's pulled in and very formal.

134
00:06:15,942 --> 00:06:20,102
And Merida is always more relaxed
and kind of has her head elsewhere.

135
00:06:24,851 --> 00:06:26,691
We had this idea for just one day.

136
00:06:27,053 --> 00:06:30,653
Ascene for a day in the life of Merida,
which had all these elements in there.

137
00:06:31,258 --> 00:06:34,037
And then we decided to make it
like this mini montage

138
00:06:34,527 --> 00:06:39,887
so we get that she's being kind of
ruled or run by her mom constantly

139
00:06:40,734 --> 00:06:43,544
day after day after day after day
after day

140
00:06:44,037 --> 00:06:48,347
with all these lessons,
and these reasons to be a princess.

141
00:06:49,042 --> 00:06:51,821
So that when she gets her day
it's a real breakout.

142
00:06:54,314 --> 00:06:57,594
We had a big issue because
we had a princess in this movie,

143
00:06:58,151 --> 00:07:02,341
and because this is fairly
familiar ground with Disney films,

144
00:07:03,023 --> 00:07:04,513
and other movies
that have a princess in it,

145
00:07:04,824 --> 00:07:09,864
that we really wanted to define what
everybody thinks a princess is

146
00:07:10,664 --> 00:07:11,563
in the opening,

147
00:07:11,798 --> 00:07:14,408
so that we can break it
in this sequence once she gets out.

148
00:07:14,868 --> 00:07:16,068
I mean, she ends up...

149
00:07:16,336 --> 00:07:18,416
She's riding through the woods
and having this great day.

150
00:07:18,805 --> 00:07:20,145
And we see her skills with the arrow.

151
00:07:20,440 --> 00:07:22,490
How much she's developed
since the beginning of the film

152
00:07:22,876 --> 00:07:23,955
when she couldn't hit nothing.

153
00:07:24,210 --> 00:07:27,810
How capable and athletic she is,
how brave and bold she is.

154
00:07:28,415 --> 00:07:30,635
And, later on,
she's even mucking out her own stall.

155
00:07:31,051 --> 00:07:34,421
You don't really see princesses
mucking out their stalls in any movies.

156
00:07:34,988 --> 00:07:38,528
So, we're visually saying, "This is not
the princess you think she is.

157
00:07:39,125 --> 00:07:43,165
"She is not timid, a faint heart,
waiting for Prince Charming to come.

158
00:07:43,830 --> 00:07:45,909
"She's going to do it all herself."

159
00:07:46,299 --> 00:07:49,049
Well, this sequence in particular
is really a response to

160
00:07:49,536 --> 00:07:50,676
the sequence with her mother.

161
00:07:50,937 --> 00:07:53,047
The camera was very still
and muted colors.

162
00:07:53,440 --> 00:07:56,840
Where here, the camera is very active
and the colors are bright.

163
00:07:57,410 --> 00:08:02,190
So it's kind of comparing what Merida is
truly feeling during both sequences.

164
00:08:02,949 --> 00:08:06,759
Right. Life in the castle is this drab,
boring, restrictive place.

165
00:08:07,387 --> 00:08:10,167
But once she's out on Angus
riding around,

166
00:08:10,657 --> 00:08:12,556
then it becomes
this big, bold free place.

167
00:08:12,926 --> 00:08:15,916
And she's much more in her element,
her environment.

168
00:08:16,429 --> 00:08:18,539
And she's ultimately
exploring who she is.

169
00:08:18,932 --> 00:08:23,352
And finding things that she likes
and are inspiring to her, and risking.

170
00:08:24,070 --> 00:08:25,880
I mean, she almost slips
and falls off of this rock.

171
00:08:26,239 --> 00:08:27,989
We call that the Crone's Tooth.

172
00:08:28,341 --> 00:08:30,891
Those are the Fire Falls
which was inspired by

173
00:08:31,344 --> 00:08:34,443
this natural phenomenon that actually
happens in the United States

174
00:08:34,981 --> 00:08:37,530
in Yosemite National Park
at a certain time of year.

175
00:08:37,984 --> 00:08:41,644
The sun, when it sets,
casts this light on the falls

176
00:08:42,255 --> 00:08:45,625
that makes it catch on fire
and they call that the Firefalls.

177
00:08:48,261 --> 00:08:49,810
There are three songs in the movie.

178
00:08:50,130 --> 00:08:53,350
And this is the first song written by
our very own Alex Mandel

179
00:08:53,900 --> 00:08:56,560
who l asked to do these as temp songs

180
00:08:57,037 --> 00:08:59,527
‘cause we needed something
in these positions.

181
00:08:59,973 --> 00:09:02,992
And we listened to 'em so much
and everybody really liked 'em.

182
00:09:03,510 --> 00:09:05,790
And I remember John Lasseter
and Andrew Stanton saying,

183
00:09:06,212 --> 00:09:08,932
"Who did those songs?
Those are great!"

184
00:09:09,416 --> 00:09:13,366
And so we kept them in the movie,
and got them re-recorded

185
00:09:14,020 --> 00:09:16,829
and found a Scottish singer
and they turned out really great.

186
00:09:20,994 --> 00:09:22,334
One thing that we were
talking about is that

187
00:09:22,629 --> 00:09:24,529
the teenager is
always late to the dinner table.

188
00:09:24,898 --> 00:09:27,418
And they've already eaten usually
or have gotten some snack

189
00:09:27,867 --> 00:09:29,857
and she's always
stuffing her face before.

190
00:09:30,236 --> 00:09:34,076
So it was a bigger thing at one point,
and we just scaled it down to

191
00:09:34,707 --> 00:09:36,516
the couple shots of her
entering the kitchen,

192
00:09:36,876 --> 00:09:38,656
having a couple of bites, and nibbling.

193
00:09:39,012 --> 00:09:42,291
So that she can steal this
platter of cupcakes for her brothers.

194
00:09:44,050 --> 00:09:46,890
What I like about the scene that you,
I think, were trying to establish was

195
00:09:47,387 --> 00:09:48,967
you're setting up
the space of the castle.

196
00:09:49,289 --> 00:09:51,899
You're trying to introduce the castle
and the family as a unit.

197
00:09:52,358 --> 00:09:55,348
So you're trying to get a lot of space
associated for the audience.

198
00:09:56,563 --> 00:09:58,143
So we want to meet these
characters that they're in

199
00:09:58,465 --> 00:10:00,305
this exotic time period for us.

200
00:10:00,667 --> 00:10:04,177
And so we want to see them in a way
that we recognize the situation totally.

201
00:10:04,771 --> 00:10:08,050
And then we can get on board with
the characters much more easily.

202
00:10:08,608 --> 00:10:09,537
It's a typical day.

203
00:10:09,776 --> 00:10:14,026
You want to set up the normal day
before you see the extraordinary day.

204
00:10:14,714 --> 00:10:17,734
It's really hard when you've got
something that's in the round here.

205
00:10:18,251 --> 00:10:20,391
You've got a four-sided table
with characters on each side

206
00:10:20,787 --> 00:10:21,927
to keep 'em straight.

207
00:10:22,188 --> 00:10:25,818
So there is a pattern to
the cutting of who you see

208
00:10:26,426 --> 00:10:29,056
and when and who locks down
on one side or the other.

209
00:10:29,529 --> 00:10:32,779
With Fergus, usually Merida's head's
there on the left side of the screen.

210
00:10:33,333 --> 00:10:36,293
And then with Mom, Merida's
head's on the other side of the screen,

211
00:10:36,803 --> 00:10:37,793
on the right side of the screen.

212
00:10:38,037 --> 00:10:40,527
So we know where Mom is
in relation to Dad.

213
00:10:40,974 --> 00:10:42,204
And where the triplets are.

214
00:10:42,475 --> 00:10:44,995
The filmmaking is all there
to try and lock us down into place.

215
00:10:45,445 --> 00:10:47,195
And it also really illustrates
the difference in the relationship

216
00:10:47,547 --> 00:10:48,537
between Mom and Dad.

217
00:10:48,781 --> 00:10:51,531
Where she has this very
sweet relationship with her father.

218
00:10:52,018 --> 00:10:54,828
And then her mother is barely
paying attention to her at this point.

219
00:10:55,321 --> 00:10:57,051
Right. And we wanted to
switch that old dynamic

220
00:10:57,390 --> 00:11:00,490
of Dad's usually reading
at the dinner table with the newspaper.

221
00:11:01,027 --> 00:11:02,107
It's actually Mom, you know,

222
00:11:02,362 --> 00:11:04,911
she has all of her affairs of state
and the castle,

223
00:11:05,365 --> 00:11:07,945
you know, accounts and things,
so she's the business one

224
00:11:08,401 --> 00:11:09,981
while Dad is engaging with the family.

225
00:11:10,303 --> 00:11:12,913
And here's to set up a dynamic of just
between Merida and the triplets

226
00:11:13,373 --> 00:11:15,043
that they're not antagonistic
towards one another.

227
00:11:15,375 --> 00:11:17,955
They help each other out, and
you'll see that again later on in the film.

228
00:11:18,411 --> 00:11:20,141
Ted Mathot actually had this great gag

229
00:11:20,480 --> 00:11:23,820
when the dogs jump up
and try and start eating Fergus' food,

230
00:11:24,384 --> 00:11:26,994
and he knocks them away.
And I thought that was just hilarious.

231
00:11:27,453 --> 00:11:30,173
