steer her away from Mor'du.

1617
01:17:02,051 --> 01:17:04,891
And there's great acting
from Billy Connolly in this

1618
01:17:05,387 --> 01:17:06,376
to get that rage out of him.

1619
01:17:06,622 --> 01:17:09,172
Because he's been
the jolly Scotsman the whole time,

1620
01:17:09,625 --> 01:17:12,555
to really get him to yell and roar,
and Billy was all game for it.

1621
01:17:13,062 --> 01:17:15,342
And to be fierce, he was terrific at that.

1622
01:17:15,798 --> 01:17:16,968
This took a really long time to block.

1623
01:17:17,233 --> 01:17:18,573
Yeah, well this was
one of the first things

1624
01:17:18,868 --> 01:17:20,568
-when I came on that we worked on.
-Right, right.

1625
01:17:20,903 --> 01:17:24,063
That we kind of reboarded and set,
and then it went away

1626
01:17:24,607 --> 01:17:26,447
and then it wasn't until almost
near the end of the process

1627
01:17:26,809 --> 01:17:29,299
where we came back into it
with Rob Anderson and his layout team

1628
01:17:29,745 --> 01:17:31,495
and got it all situated and set.

1629
01:17:31,847 --> 01:17:32,956
Well, we didn't have
all the characters either.

1630
01:17:33,215 --> 01:17:35,115
-Exactly.
-We were waiting for character design

1631
01:17:35,484 --> 01:17:36,504
and to be realized.

1632
01:17:37,319 --> 01:17:39,629
But we were already thinking about
what it needed to be.

1633
01:17:41,690 --> 01:17:44,320
We had the dogs in the beginning
of this sequence and they disappeared.

1634
01:17:44,827 --> 01:17:46,437
And I'm all, "Oh, my gosh."

1635
01:17:46,762 --> 01:17:48,722
It's already being animated and
we're already lighting it

1636
01:17:49,098 --> 01:17:50,998
and I'm all, "Where are my dogs?
Wouldn't they do anything?"

1637
01:17:51,367 --> 01:17:53,887
So we managed to sneak them
into a couple of shots

1638
01:17:54,336 --> 01:17:55,596
and see 'em get walloped by the bear.

1639
01:17:55,871 --> 01:17:57,211
So, that explains
why they're not around.

1640
01:17:57,506 --> 01:18:00,526
Because, back in the day,
the dogs would be all over that bear.

1641
01:18:01,043 --> 01:18:04,003
So many plates to spin that
you forget about certain elements.

1642
01:18:04,880 --> 01:18:06,220
-But they will come back to haunt you.
-Yeah.

1643
01:18:06,515 --> 01:18:08,005
Sometimes you don't want to
draw attention to something.

1644
01:18:08,317 --> 01:18:09,837
You don't want the audience
to worry about either.

1645
01:18:10,152 --> 01:18:13,402
Like the audience is hardly worrying
about where the dogs are at this point.

1646
01:18:13,956 --> 01:18:15,446
They're totally caught up
in Mor'du, so...

1647
01:18:15,758 --> 01:18:17,278
But if we could balance it just right

1648
01:18:17,593 --> 01:18:20,083
to cheat them that
we've explained why they're not there,

1649
01:18:20,529 --> 01:18:21,579
why there are no horses there,

1650
01:18:21,830 --> 01:18:24,050
that everybody's backed off
without showing it,

1651
01:18:24,466 --> 01:18:27,126
then it doesn't pull you out
without having any questions.

1652
01:18:28,270 --> 01:18:29,700
Gary Rydstrom and E.J. Holowicki

1653
01:18:30,005 --> 01:18:32,055
did an amazing job
with the bear vocals in this movie.

1654
01:18:32,441 --> 01:18:34,581
Oh, yeah, hearing the very
different aspects of them.

1655
01:18:34,977 --> 01:18:37,937
Yeah, there was a huge amount of
design work that went into their voices.

1656
01:18:38,581 --> 01:18:40,831
-And it's not all just bear sounds.
-Right.

1657
01:18:41,250 --> 01:18:43,800
And there was a version in this
where Mom was turning back and forth

1658
01:18:44,253 --> 01:18:46,623
between herself and a bear
during this fight.

1659
01:18:47,056 --> 01:18:50,925
Right. From bear mode to Mom-bear,
to bear mode to Mom-bear.

1660
01:18:51,560 --> 01:18:54,960
And it just, all these ideas
which were kind of great ideas on paper

1661
01:18:55,531 --> 01:18:58,461
that we would try,
and we'd try everything

1662
01:18:58,968 --> 01:19:01,108
to find that right concoction,

1663
01:19:01,503 --> 01:19:04,492
that right chemical explosion
of all the right things.

1664
01:19:05,007 --> 01:19:08,376
And we end up throwing out
a lot of stuff.

1665
01:19:08,944 --> 01:19:11,054
It becomes too complex.

1666
01:19:11,447 --> 01:19:13,407
And I wanted to catch the audience
by surprise with this,

1667
01:19:13,782 --> 01:19:15,512
where you know they were finished,

1668
01:19:15,851 --> 01:19:19,191
but then, it was Mom ultimately
and her kind of smarts.

1669
01:19:19,755 --> 01:19:21,925
She couldn't beat 'em physically,
but getting the help

1670
01:19:22,324 --> 01:19:25,344
from this huge stone column
to crush the bear actually did it.

1671
01:19:25,861 --> 01:19:29,581
That she recognizes that crack
and she could make it bigger.

1672
01:19:30,199 --> 01:19:31,598
It doesn't work
when she wants it to work,

1673
01:19:31,900 --> 01:19:33,629
but eventually there's a slow give away.

1674
01:19:33,969 --> 01:19:37,629
That's kind of almost my homage
to Force 10 From Navarone

1675
01:19:38,240 --> 01:19:40,260
when they blow up the dam
to save everybody,

1676
01:19:40,643 --> 01:19:42,453
but then the dam doesn't
break right away,

1677
01:19:42,811 --> 01:19:45,741
and then it breaks later
and washes away all the Nazis, yeah.

1678
01:19:46,548 --> 01:19:47,888
And we wanted to resolve Mor'du

1679
01:19:48,450 --> 01:19:49,559
instead of just kill him.

1680
01:19:49,852 --> 01:19:52,541
So we had this idea
of Mor'du gets killed,

1681
01:19:53,022 --> 01:19:56,532
and that releases his spirit to then,
how apropos, to become a wisp,

1682
01:19:57,126 --> 01:20:00,936
to then warn others or lead them away
from these negative fates.

1683
01:20:01,563 --> 01:20:03,843
Yeah, I really liked the idea
of resolving his story,

1684
01:20:04,266 --> 01:20:06,726
so he's not just this dead
carcass under the rock.

1685
01:20:07,169 --> 01:20:10,599
He's like the soul of that guy,
however nasty he was,

1686
01:20:11,173 --> 01:20:15,862
gets redeemed, somehow, just by being
released by another enchanted bear.

1687
01:20:16,612 --> 01:20:18,512
-Yeah.
-He started out being purely a bear.

1688
01:20:18,881 --> 01:20:19,811
There were different versions.

1689
01:20:20,049 --> 01:20:22,329
There was versions where
there was less magic around him.

1690
01:20:22,751 --> 01:20:25,211
And we weren't being as clear
in different versions.

1691
01:20:25,654 --> 01:20:28,554
We wanted there to be lore
around him like Moby Dick,

1692
01:20:29,058 --> 01:20:30,758
but that we didn't know
where he came from.

1693
01:20:31,093 --> 01:20:32,903
And then as the story developed,

1694
01:20:33,262 --> 01:20:35,222
it became more obvious
that he was somebody.

1695
01:20:35,597 --> 01:20:36,496
And I liked that more because

1696
01:20:36,732 --> 01:20:39,012
it feels more like a magical world
that we created.

1697
01:20:39,435 --> 01:20:42,170
It's a great storyline to help parallel
what Merida is about to go through

1698
01:20:42,171 --> 01:20:43,541
It's a great storyline to help parallel
what Merida is about to go through

1699
01:20:43,839 --> 01:20:46,939
and what the possible outcome
for Mom is going to be.

1700
01:20:48,777 --> 01:20:52,647
This was probably, for me,
one of the hardest sequences to do,

1701
01:20:53,282 --> 01:20:55,712
was this end moment to kind of tie up

1702
01:20:56,151 --> 01:21:00,371
how the magic actually
works with the words and the tapestry,

1703
01:21:01,056 --> 01:21:03,665
making the second sunrise happen.

1704
01:21:04,126 --> 01:21:08,076
When does Mom turn into the bear
so that you know the game is over,

1705
01:21:08,731 --> 01:21:12,651
so that we can be sad and crying?
That no matter how hard Merida tried,

1706
01:21:13,302 --> 01:21:14,442
even though she's learned her lesson,

1707
01:21:14,703 --> 01:21:16,953
she wants her mom back,
she still kind of failed.

1708
01:21:17,373 --> 01:21:20,833
Which I think is a great thing
for kids and adults to understand

1709
01:21:21,410 --> 01:21:23,630
that there are consequences
to our actions.

1710
01:21:24,046 --> 01:21:25,976
And we can't just be selfish.

1711
01:21:26,348 --> 01:21:30,268
We have to think about
what's going to happen a little bit more.

1712
01:21:30,919 --> 01:21:33,789
But getting this to work just right
was really difficult.

1713
01:21:34,790 --> 01:21:36,840
Getting the second sunrise in there,

1714
01:21:37,226 --> 01:21:39,806
putting it back in the ring of stones
as the focal point.

1715
01:21:40,262 --> 01:21:42,192
We would go around and around
about how that actually worked.

1716
01:21:42,598 --> 01:21:44,878
But I think,
once we finally figured this out,

1717
01:21:45,300 --> 01:21:46,970
and that we actually
had the ticking clock,

1718
01:21:47,336 --> 01:21:49,206
the visual ticking clock of the sun rising

1719
01:21:49,571 --> 01:21:52,791
and the sunlight coming down
the stones and across the ground,

1720
01:21:53,342 --> 01:21:58,352
really gave it this extra little bit of kick
in the sequence

1721
01:21:59,148 --> 01:22:01,228
to realize when it was actually over.

1722
01:22:01,617 --> 01:22:03,897
And when she says, "I love you,"
just before the sun hits her,

1723
01:22:04,319 --> 01:22:06,069
and then once it hits the tapestry

1724
01:22:06,422 --> 01:22:07,821
that changes Mom back
instantaneously

1725
01:22:08,123 --> 01:22:10,312
and, again,
we don't see that magic happen.

1726
01:22:10,726 --> 01:22:12,896
We don't see that scene,
it just happens.

1727
01:22:13,295 --> 01:22:14,725
Yeah, we wanted to
mute the magic though.

1728
01:22:15,030 --> 01:22:17,370
We didn't want to see
a giant spectacle of special effects here.

1729
01:22:17,800 --> 01:22:22,490
We wanted to just feel like this moment
was very personal and very small.

1730
01:22:23,238 --> 01:22:25,868
Yeah, it's unexplained,
and it makes it more intimate,

1731
01:22:26,341 --> 01:22:30,381
instead of just something that happens
that's fireworks or blue swirly lights

1732
01:22:31,046 --> 01:22:33,626
or anything like that,
that everybody can witness and see.

1733
01:22:34,082 --> 01:22:37,272
It's just... Blink! She's back to normal.

1734
01:22:38,720 --> 01:22:40,330
The ending is all about the balance.

1735
01:22:40,656 --> 01:22:43,406
We have all these strings
that we have to tie up.

1736
01:22:43,892 --> 01:22:44,912
So it's really tricky.

1737
01:22:45,160 --> 01:22:47,240
The ending of a film is always really

1738
01:22:47,629 --> 01:22:49,679
one of the trickiest things
there is in filmmaking,

1739
01:22:50,065 --> 01:22:53,254
‘cause there's always
these emotional qualities to it

1740
01:22:53,802 --> 01:22:59,892
that you have to just arrange just right
to have the effect that you really want.

1741
01:23:00,843 --> 01:23:03,423
So there was a lot going on
here that we had to navigate,

1742
01:23:03,879 --> 01:23:08,159
and how much of what to make it work
and not just seem overbearing.

1743
01:23:10,152 --> 01:23:13,312
It seems like near the end of a movie
the audience's perceptions speed up.

1744
01:23:13,856 --> 01:23:16,286
And so, you're kind of
weighing this idea

1745
01:23:16,992 --> 01:23:19,482
of how long does it take you
to get to the climax?

1746
01:23:19,928 --> 01:23:22,117
‘Cause they're kind of maybe
ahead of you at this point.

1747
01:23:22,531 --> 01:23:25,931
And so you want to make sure
you're dishing it out at the right pace

1748
01:23:26,502 --> 01:23:28,342
for the audience to be receiving it.

1749
01:23:28,704 --> 01:23:30,433
And sometimes we find we lag too much

1750
01:23:30,772 --> 01:23:33,322
and we want to get to it a little sooner
than we thought we did.

1751
01:23:38,146 --> 01:23:42,746
This was, technically, one of
the hardest shots we had in the movie

1752
01:23:43,485 --> 01:23:47,025
because of the rate of the camera move
and the pan that was in it,

1753
01:23:47,623 --> 01:23:49,843
and you're shooting
24 frames a second,

1754
01:23:50,259 --> 01:23:53,069
you get a strobing, this stutter.

1755
01:23:53,562 --> 01:23:57,312
And, to work that out,
we had to slow down the move,

1756
01:23:57,933 --> 01:24:00,513
make it not as long,
pan slower or faster.

1757
01:24:00,969 --> 01:24:02,169
But I wanted to see all the stuff,

1758
01:24:02,437 --> 01:24:05,947
so we did some magic tricks
and worked it out.

1759
01:24:07,409 --> 01:24:09,989
But that's one of the things
that you run into in film.

1760
01:24:10,445 --> 01:24:12,465
And then I like getting into...

1761
01:24:12,848 --> 01:24:16,388
Merida kind of starts off the movie
with her narration,

1762
01:24:16,985 --> 01:24:20,934
and here she ends her narration
with that moral of the story.

1763
01:24:21,857 --> 01:24:27,397
And I think it works great with
Mumford & Sons' song in this moment,

1764
01:24:28,263 --> 01:24:30,663
that there's this little hole cut out
for Merida to say her piece,

1765
01:24:31,099 --> 01:24:33,679
and then you go back into the song,
which kind of sums it all up.

1766
01:24:34,136 --> 01:24:36,571
I'm really glad that
Mumford & Sons came on board

1767
01:24:36,572 --> 01:24:38,212
I'm really glad that
Mumford & Sons came on board

1768
01:24:38,907 --> 01:24:42,217
and agreed to do the final song,
our final song moment in the movie.

1769
01:24:42,778 --> 01:24:46,348
-And Birdy.
-And Birdy, she sings it great.

1770
01:24:47,950 --> 01:24:52,139
It just encapsulates the whole story
in this nice kind of 1-2-3 bit.

1771
01:24:52,821 --> 01:24:55,781
Even their emotional arc,
Merida's emotional arc of where she is,

1772
01:24:56,291 --> 01:24:58,191
just sums up everything perfectly.

